# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] The **1965 Conservative Party leadership election** was held in July 1965 to elect Alec Douglas-Home's successor as Leader of the Conservative Party.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] Edward Heath, the Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer, was elected with 50.4 per cent of the vote, defeating Reginald Maudling, the Shadow Foreign Secretary on 44.6 per cent.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] It was the first formal leadership election to be held by the Parliamentary Conservative Party.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] The plans for how the election would work were published in February 1965, and agreed upon by the parliamentary party thereafter.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] The former prime minister Alec Douglas-Home triggered the election on 23 July 1965, by resigning at a full meeting of the 1922 Committee in committee room 14.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] It was widely assumed that both Edward Heath, Shadow Chancellor, and Reginald Maudling, Shadow Foreign Secretary, would stand.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] Members of the "magic circle" of old Etonians chose not to contend the election, with widespread agreement that a younger and modern face was needed to front the Conservative Party.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] Another potential "modernising" candidate, Iain Macleod, ruled himself out immediately.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] He might have received 40 to 45 votes had he stood, but he instead endorsed Heath.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] Other names that were seen as possible contenders were Quintin Hogg, Peter Thorneycroft and Enoch Powell, Shadow Transport Minister (who eventually did stand).
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] Some were angered by Powell's candidature, as a complication in an otherwise clear contest.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] Maudling, the most experienced and publicly known of the candidates, was generally considered to be the favourite.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] Heath's prospects were seen as either tie-ing or preventing Maudling from reaching the 15% lead needed to win outright.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] It was also thought that Powell would take support away from Heath, whose backers predominantly came from northern England and industrial cities (such as Birmingham and Wolverhampton), as opposed to Maudling's geographically wider support.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] Heath, however, fought a more effective leadership campaign, organised by his young lieutenant Peter Walker, and by the eve of the election, the Heath camp believed they had a clear lead.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] Maudling, by contrast, fought a lacklustre campaign.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] He assumed, for example, that William Whitelaw would vote for him, but he voted for Heath.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] The election was managed by the Chairman of the 1922 Committee, Sir William Anstruther-Gray.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] The rules in place required the victor to have both an absolute majority (which Heath had narrowly achieved) and, in the first ballot, at least a 15% lead of votes actually cast (not counting abstaining members - this would be changed in the mid-1970s review of the rules).
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] As Heath had not achieved the latter hurdle, the election could therefore have gone to further rounds.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] However, Maudling conceded defeat and Heath was duly declared leader.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] Powell had not expected to win, but said he had "left his visiting card", i.e. publicly demonstrated himself to be a potential future leader.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] However, the 1965 leadership contest showed Powell's lack of support in the Parliamentary Party, and thereafter Heath felt able to call his bluff.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] In 1968 Heath sacked Powell from the Conservative front bench after Powell had delivered the Rivers of Blood speech, although he held great sway over public opinion in the following years.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1965-conservative-party-leadership-election] However, by the next time a leadership vote was held (in 1975) he had become an Ulster Unionist and so was no longer eligible.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on Thursday 31 March 1966.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] The result was a landslide victory for the Labour Party led by incumbent Prime Minister Harold Wilson.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] Wilson decided to call a snap election since his government, elected a mere 17 months previously, in 1964, had an unworkably small majority of only four MPs.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] The Labour government was returned following this snap election with a much larger majority of 96 seats.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] This was the last British general election in which the voting age was 21; Wilson's government passed an amendment to the Representation of the People Act in 1969 to include eligibility to vote at the age of 18, which was in place for the next general election in 1970.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] This was the only election between 1945 and 1997 in which the Labour Party won a workable majority sustainable to last a full term.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] In the next seven general elections, the Labour Party would win a majority of seats only once (October 1974) and would lose five elections to the Conservatives.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] This election is also noted for the Labour Party achieving its third-highest vote-share (48%) and second-largest total number of votes in its history (the largest vote-share being the 49.7% achieved in the 1945 election).
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] Prior to the 1966 general election, Labour had performed poorly in local elections in 1965, and lost a by-election, cutting their majority to just two.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] Shortly after the local elections, the leader of the Conservative Party Alec Douglas-Home was replaced by Edward Heath in the 1965 leadership election.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] Despite setbacks and a small majority, Labour believed it had an advantage due to the disorientation from the change of leadership at the Conservative Party, the improvement of economic conditions under its brief government, and a victory at the 1966 Kingston upon Hull North by-election.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives had not had much time to prepare their campaign, although it was more professional than previously.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] There had been little time for Heath to become well known among the British public, having led the party for just eight months before the election.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] For the Liberal Party, money was an issue: two elections in the space of just two years had left the party in a tight financial position and had to field fewer candidates.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour ran its campaign with the slogan "You know Labour government works" and avoided commenting on controversial issues such as European integration, trade unions, and nationalisation.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] The election night was broadcast live on the BBC, was presented by Cliff Michelmore, Ian Trethowan, Robin Day, Robert McKenzie and David Butler.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was replayed on the BBC Parliament channel on the 40th anniversary of the event, and again in 2016 to mark the 50th anniversary of the election.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] The Prime Minister, Harold Wilson, announced on 28 February that Parliament would be dissolved on 10 March, for an election to be held on 31 March.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] The Labour Party performed very well in the election and expanded its previously slim majority against the Conservative opposition to 97 seats, accomplishing a net gain of 47 seats.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] It won 364 seats from 48 per cent of the vote, against 253 seats from 41.4 per cent for the Conservatives and 12 seats from 8 per cent for the Liberals.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] A major reason for the Labour victory was the revitalization of the party's working-class support in the 1960s.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] It captured its highest support yet from manual laborers at 69 per cent, as well as its best performance for non-manual laborers since 1945.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] The government also appealed to both the right wing of the party with its cabinet dominated by junior ministers of the Attlee ministry as well as the left wing by the presence of officials such as Prime Minister Wilson, Richard Crossman, Barbara Castle, and Frank Cousins.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] Although the party would go on to win more seats under Tony Blair in 1997 and 2001, and again under Keir Starmer in 2024, Labour have never since matched the 48% of the popular vote they won in 1966.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1966-united-kingdom-general-election] These declarations were covered live by the BBC where the returning officer was heard to say "duly elected".
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on Thursday 18 June 1970.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] It resulted in a surprise victory for the Conservative Party under leader Edward Heath, which defeated the governing Labour Party under Prime Minister Harold Wilson.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Party, under its new leader Jeremy Thorpe, lost half its seats.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives, including the Ulster Unionist Party (UUP), secured a majority of 30 seats.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] This general election was the first in which people could vote from the age of 18, after passage of the Representation of the People Act the previous year, and the first UK election in which party affiliations of candidates were put on the ballots.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Most opinion polls prior to the election indicated a comfortable Labour victory, and put Labour up to 12.4% ahead of the Conservatives.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] On election day, however, a late swing gave the Conservatives a 3.4% lead and ended almost six years of Labour government, although Wilson remained leader of the Labour Party in opposition.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Writing in the aftermath of the election, the political scientist Richard Rose described the Conservative victory as "surprising" and noted a significant shift in votes between the two main parties.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] *The Times* journalist George Clark wrote that the election would be "remembered as the occasion when the people of the United Kingdom hurled the findings of the opinion polls back into the faces of the pollsters".
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Frontbench Labour politicians George Brown and Jennie Lee were voted out at this election.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] This marked the end of a series of elections where both main parties won over 40% of the vote.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] This would not occur again for the Conservatives for nine years; Labour would wait 27.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] The result was cast as a two-party politics outcome, with no third party reaching 10% of the (total) vote.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Such an outcome would not happen again until the 2017 election.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was the last in which a nationwide UK party gained seats in Northern Ireland.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] The UUP sat with the Conservative Party at Westminster, traditionally taking the Conservative parliamentary whip.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] To all intents and purposes the UUP functioned as the Northern Ireland branch of the Conservative Party.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] However, hardline unionist Ian Paisley unseated the UUP incumbent in North Antrim, a clear sign that the UUP's complete dominance over unionist politics in Northern Ireland was already starting to weaken.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] In 1972, in protest over the permanent prorogation of the Parliament of Northern Ireland, Westminster UUP MPs withdrew from the alliance.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Interviewed by Robin Day, the outgoing Prime Minister Harold Wilson highlighted the possibility that "complacency engendered by the opinion polls" may have resulted in a poor turnout of Labour supporters.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] As defending world champions, England's venture in the World Cup attracted a much keener public interest than the general election did.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] However an analysis by pollster Matt Singh for the 50th anniversary of the election concluded that the late swing had been caused by the weak economic data and that there was "no evidence" that the World Cup had influenced the outcome.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] American pollster Douglas Schoen and Oxford University academic R.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Johnson asserted that Enoch Powell had attracted 2.5 million votes to the Conservatives, although the Conservative vote only increased by 1.7 million.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Johnson later stated "It became clear that Powell had won the 1970 election for the Tories ... of all those who had switched their vote from one party to another, 50 per cent were working class Powellites".
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Election night commentators Michael Barratt and Jeffrey Preece dismissed any special "Powell factor", as did Conservative MPs Reginald Maudling, Timothy Raison and Hugh Dykes.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] The 1970–74 Parliament has to date been the only time since the 1924–29 Parliament in which the Conservative Party were only in government for one term before returning to opposition.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] The most notable casualty of the election was George Brown, deputy leader of the Labour Party, who lost to the Conservative candidate in the Belper constituency.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour Minister for the Arts, Jennie Lee lost her Cannock seat, held by Labour since 1935 on a swing of 10.7% to the Conservatives in what Richard Rose called "the biggest upset" of the election.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Unusually for the Liberal Party, the by-elections between 1966 and 1970 had proved almost fruitless, with many Liberal candidates losing deposits.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] The one exception was its by-election gain of Birmingham Ladywood in June 1969; this was promptly lost in the 1970 general election.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] The party found itself struggling to introduce its new leader Jeremy Thorpe to the public, owing to the extensive coverage and attention paid to Enoch Powell.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] The election result was poor for the Liberals, with Thorpe only narrowly winning his own seat in North Devon.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Indeed, of the six MPs returned, three (Thorpe, David Steel and John Pardoe) were elected by a majority of less than 1,000 votes.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] The BBC's election coverage was led by Cliff Michelmore, along with Robin Day, David Butler and Robert McKenzie.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] There were periodic cutaways to the BBC regions.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] This coverage has been rerun on BBC Parliament on several occasions, including on 18 July 2005 as a tribute to Edward Heath after his death the previous day.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Its most recent screening was on the 20th of June 2020, to commemorate the 50th anniversary of its first transmission.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] The BBC coverage was parodied by *Monty Python's Flying Circus* in its famous "Election Night Special" sketch.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Both BBC and ITN carried their 1970 election night broadcasts in colour, although segments broadcast from some remote locations and some BBC and ITN regional bureaus were transmitted in black-and-white.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Some ITV regions were not yet broadcasting in colour at the time of the 1970 elections.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] The right to vote in this election was widened by the Labour government's Sixth Reform Act, which reduced the voting age from 21 to 18 years.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] The United Kingdom was the first major democratic nation to extend suffrage to this age group.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Case law subsequently established the right for undergraduate students to vote in the constituency of their university.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] This followed an appeal to the High Court.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] The Prime Minister, Harold Wilson, visited Buckingham Palace on 18 May and asked the Queen to dissolve Parliament on 29 May, announcing that the election would be held on 18 June.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Summary of the final polling results before the general election.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] This was the first general election where 18-year-olds had the right to vote.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Therefore, despite 1.1 million more people voting in 1970 compared to 1966, turnout actually fell by 3%.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] This 72% turnout was the lowest since the 1935 general election and compared with a post-War high of 84% in 1950.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Professor Richard Rose described the low turnout, which he noted was "one of the lowest since the introduction of the democratic franchise", as surprising to politician and pollsters.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Changes to electoral law as part of the Representation of the People Act 1969 had made postal voting easier and polling stations were open an hour later than in past elections, and this would have been expected to improve turnout.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] On top of this it was reported by Rose that an estimated 25% of 18- to 21-year-olds who were now eligible to vote had not put their names on the electoral register, meaning the turnout was even lower than the percentage figure suggested.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Rose also argued that the turnout figures in Britain were "now among the lowest in the Western world." Because the previous election had been in 1966, some people had not had their chance to vote in a general election until the age of 25.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour's number of votes, 12.2 million, was ironically the same amount they had needed to win in 1964.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservative vote surge cost Labour in many marginal seats.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] Rose suggested the absolute fall in the number of Labour votes suggested that many of the party's supporters had decided to abstain.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] For the Liberals, a small 1% drop in their vote share saw them lose 6 seats, 3 of which were held by the narrowest of margins.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] In the end the Conservatives achieved a swing of 4.7%, enough to give them a comfortable working majority.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] As for the smaller parties, they increased their number in the Commons from 2 to 6 seats.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1970-united-kingdom-general-election] The Scottish National Party won its first ever seat at a general election (they had won several by-elections previously, going back as far as 1945), although they did lose Hamilton, which they won in a by-election in 1967.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] A miners' strike took place in the United Kingdom in 1972 as a result of a dispute over pay between the National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) and the Conservative Edward Heath government.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] Miners' wages had not kept pace with those of other industrial workers since 1960.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] The strike began on 9 January 1972 and ended on 28 February 1972, when the miners returned to work.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] The strike was called by the National Executive Committee of the NUM and ended when the miners accepted an improved pay offer in a ballot.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] It was the first time since 1926 that British miners had been on official strike, but there had been a widespread unofficial strike in 1969.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] Competition from cheap oil imports arrived in the late 1950s and the coal industry began to suffer from increasing losses.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] In 1960 Alf Robens became the chairman of the National Coal Board (NCB), and he introduced a policy concentrating on the most productive pits.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] During his ten-year tenure, productivity increased by 70%, but with far fewer pits and a much reduced workforce.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] In 1956, 700,000 men produced 207 million tons of coal; by 1971, fewer than 290,000 workers were producing 133 million tons at 292 collieries.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] Despite this, the NCB's coal activities were still running at a loss in 1970, putting pressure on the board to hold down pay increases.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] The strike occurred because wage negotiations between the NUM and the National Coal Board of the United Kingdom had broken down.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] During the 1950s, the wages of miners went up from a prewar position of 84th to near the top in the league table of the wages earned by industrial workers, and by 1960, miners' wages were 7.4% above the average pay of workers in manufacturing industries.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] During the 1960s, however, their pay fell behind other workers, and by 1970 miners were earning 3.1% less than the average worker in manufacturing.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] By the early 1970s, hundreds of miners had left the industry in search of higher-paying factory jobs.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] It was the first time since 1926 that British miners had officially gone on strike (although there had been unofficial strikes, as recently as 1969).
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] During a parliamentary debate on the strike in its second week, both Labour and Conservative MPs praised the miners for the forbearance shown during the mass pit closures in the 1960s.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] Mine foremen and supervisors, represented by the National Association of Colliery Overmen, Deputies and Shotfirers, did not strike.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] Following some confrontations with NUM pickets, the National Coal Board adopted a policy of giving leave on full pay to any members of NACODS who faced aggressive intimidation on the way to work.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] The strike was characterised by the miners sending flying pickets to other industrial sites to persuade other workers to strike in solidarity, which led to railway workers' refusing to transport coal and power station workers' refusing to handle coal.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] Power shortages emerged, and a state of emergency was declared on 9 February, after the weather had turned cold unexpectedly and voltage had been reduced across the entire national grid.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] A miner from Hatfield Colliery, near Doncaster, Freddie Matthews, was killed by a lorry while he was picketing on 3 February 1972, and a huge crowd attended his funeral.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] The non-union lorry driver had mounted the pavement to pass the picket line and struck Matthews in the process.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] In the aftermath of the death, the picketing in the Doncaster area became more violent, with clashes reported with the NACODS members at Markham Main and Kilnhurst.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] Tom Swain, Labour MP to Derbyshire North East, remarked, "This could be the start of another Ulster in the Yorkshire coalfield." He threatened to "advocate violence" if an immediate government statement were not made on Matthews's death.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] The strike lasted seven weeks, with NUM leaders agreeing to a pay deal on 19 February, which the union claimed to have wrung about 15 extra pay concessions from the Coal Board - over and above the Wilberforce inquiry recommendations.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] Rank-and-file NUM miners agreed to the pay offer on 25 February, returning to work on 28 February, which officially ended the strike.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] The pay concessions from the Coal Board came more than a week after the Battle of Saltley Gate, when around 2,000 NUM pickets descended on a coke works in Birmingham and were later joined by thousands of workers from other industries in Birmingham.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] The result was characterised as a "victory for violence" by the Conservative Cabinet at the time, in reference to some clashes between miners and police and to some throwing of stones and bottles at lorries trying to pass the pickets.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] A volunteer force was planned in Scotland to break the miners' pickets during the strike.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] After release of government papers under the thirty-year rule, it has been revealed that civil servants, police, local authorities and other organisations worked on a secret project to gather hundreds of drivers to supply the country's power stations during the strike.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] A Royal Air Force base was to be used for the unit.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] They were to have between 400 and 600 trucks and drivers.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] Fire brigades were also contacted to provide off-duty staff and volunteer groups to cater for the coal convoys.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] The role of the volunteers was to drive in convoys to break the picketlines blocking the supply of coal to the Scottish power plants.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] The plans were never put into place because the dispute was brought to a close.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] An inquiry into miners' pay, chaired by Lord Wilberforce, was set up by the government in February 1972, as the strike was drawing to a close.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] It recommended pay increases of between £4.50 and £6 per week.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] The inadequacy of the government's response to the strike provoked re-evaluation of emergency planning.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1972-united-kingdom-miners-strike] The Cabinet Office Briefing Room (known as COBR) was created to co-ordinate responses to national and regional crises, and is still used to respond to terrorism and other national emergencies by British Government today.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The **1973 enlargement of the European Communities** was the first enlargement of the European Communities (EC), now the European Union (EU).
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Denmark, Ireland and the United Kingdom (UK) acceded to the EC on 1 January 1973.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Gibraltar and Greenland also joined the EC as part of the United Kingdom and Denmark respectively, but the Danish Faroe Islands, the other British Overseas Territories and the Crown dependencies of the United Kingdom did not join the EC.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Ireland and Denmark both held referendums in 1972 in May and October respectively, and the United Kingdom held a referendum in 1975, on membership of the EC, all which approved membership of the EC.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Norway planned to accede, but this was rejected in a referendum held in September 1972.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In 1992 Norway again applied to join, but voters again rejected the proposal in a 1994 referendum.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Greenland later withdrew from the EC on 1 January 1985 after a referendum in 1982.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] This was followed by the United Kingdom holding a referendum in 2016 on membership which resulted in the United Kingdom voting to leave the EU.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The United Kingdom was still recovering from the economic cost of the Second World War.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Ireland, while an independent state, was economically dependent on the UK, which accounted for nearly 75% of Ireland's exports, as codified in the Anglo-Irish Free trade agreement of 1966.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In 1960 the European Free Trade Association (EFTA) was established and was formed by Austria, Denmark, Norway, Portugal, Sweden, Switzerland and the United Kingdom.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] These countries were often referred to as the Outer Seven, as opposed to the Inner Six of the founding members of the European Community (EC).
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The EFTA was founded by a convention known as the Stockholm Convention in 1960, with the aim of liberalisation of trade in goods amongst its member states.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] On 31 July 1961 the United Kingdom, Ireland and Denmark applied to join the EC.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In 1963, after negotiations, France vetoed the United Kingdom's application because of the aversion of Charles de Gaulle to the UK, which he considered a "trojan horse" for the United States.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] De Gaulle resigned the French presidency in 1969.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In the 1970s, the EFTA states concluded free trade agreements with the EC.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] The **1975 Conservative Party leadership election** was held in February 1975.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] The party's sitting MPs voted Margaret Thatcher as party leader on the second ballot.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] Incumbent leader Edward Heath stood aside after the first ballot, in which he unexpectedly finished behind Thatcher.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] The Conservatives were the official Opposition to the Labour government, so Thatcher also became Leader of the Opposition.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] Edward Heath, leader of the Conservative Party and Prime Minister had called and unexpectedly lost the February 1974 general election.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] At that time the rules for electing a party leader only applied when the post was vacant and there was no way to challenge an incumbent.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] Heath faced many critics calling for either his resignation or a change in the rules for leadership elections to allow for a challenge.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] Heath eventually agreed with the 1922 Committee that there would be a review of the rules for leadership elections and subsequently he would put himself up for re-election.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] A review was conducted under the auspices of Heath's predecessor Sir Alec Douglas-Home.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] Two recommendations were made, though neither was to make a difference in 1975 (although they would prove crucial in future years).
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] The leader would henceforth be elected annually, whether the party was in opposition or government, in the period following a Queen's Speech, though in most years this would prove a formality.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] Also on the first round the requirement for a victorious candidate to have a lead of 15% over their nearest rival was modified so that this would now be 15% of the total number of MPs, not just those voting for candidates.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] This is what would ultimately deprive Margaret Thatcher of a majority in the first ballot in the leadership election held fifteen years later.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] Following the review, on 14 January 1975 Heath called a leadership election for 4 February, in order to assert his authority as leader of the party.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] Many expected the contest to be a walkover, believing there was no clear alternative to Heath after Keith Joseph had ruled himself out following controversial remarks calling on poor people to have fewer children and William Whitelaw had pledged loyalty to Heath.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] Many other shadow cabinet members pledged their support for Heath including Jim Prior, Peter Carrington, Leader in the House of Lords, and Robert Carr, Shadow Chancellor.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] However, on 20 January Margaret Thatcher opted to stand, with Airey Neave as her campaign manager, as did backbencher Hugh Fraser.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] Even then many believed that Heath would win easily.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] Thatcher's support was seen as minimal, with all the Conservative daily newspapers backing Heath (although the weekly *The Spectator* backed Thatcher).
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] As the election went on it became clear that the race was going to be much closer, as Thatcher became the clear candidate to be supported by discontented backbenchers.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] At the same time it was reported that 8 out of 10 Conservative peers and a majority of constituency organisations supported Heath.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] As Chairman of the 1922 Committee, Edward du Cann managed the election.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] As a result of the first ballot, Fraser withdrew.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] Following his defeat in the first ballot Heath asked Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer Robert Carr to "take over the functions of leader" until a new leader was elected.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-conservative-party-leadership-election] 49-year-old Thatcher became the first woman to be elected leader of a major British political party.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The Labour Party's manifesto for the October 1974 general election had promised that the people would decide through the ballot box whether to remain in the EC.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] In a 1975 pamphlet, Prime Minister Harold Wilson said: "I ask you to use your vote.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] For it is *your* vote that will now decide.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The Government will accept *your* verdict." The pamphlet also said: "Now the time has come for *you* to decide.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The Government will accept your decision — whichever way it goes." The electorate expressed significant support for continued EC membership, with 67% in favour on a national turnout of 64%.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] It was also the only national referendum to be held on the UK's relationship with Europe until the 2016 referendum on continued EU membership.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The February 1974 general election had yielded a Labour minority government, which went on to win a very small overall majority in the October 1974 general election.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Labour pledged in its February 1974 manifesto to renegotiate the terms of British accession to the EC, and then to consult the public on whether Britain should remain in the EC on the new terms, if they were acceptable to the government.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The EC heads of government agreed to a deal in Dublin on 11 March 1975; Wilson declared: "I believe that our renegotiation objectives have been substantially though not completely achieved", and said that the government would recommend a vote in favour of continued membership.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] On 9 April, the House of Commons voted by 396 to 170 to continue within the Common Market on the new terms.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Along with these developments, the government drafted a Referendum Bill, to be moved in case of a successful renegotiation.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The referendum debate and campaign was an unusual time in British politics and was the third national vote to be held in seventeen months.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] During the campaign, the Labour Cabinet was split and its members campaigned on each side of the question, an unprecedented breach of Cabinet collective responsibility.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Most votes in the House of Commons in preparation for the referendum were only carried after opposition support, and the Government faced several defeats on technical issues such as the handling and format of the referendum counts.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The referendum did temporarily achieve Harold Wilson's ambition to bring the divided Labour Party together on the European issue; however, eight years later, Labour's 1983 general election manifesto pledged withdrawal from the Communities.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] It also significantly strengthened the position of the pro-marketeer (later pro-Europe) politicians in the UK Parliament for the next thirty years; however, the issue of continued membership, despite the outcome of the referendum, was ultimately never resolved and remained contentious.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] In the decades that followed, successive UK governments integrated further into the European project by ratifying subsequent European treaties (in particular Maastricht and Lisbon) through Parliament but without any further public approval.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The UK Government did however decide against adopting the euro after the pound was forced to withdraw from the European Exchange Rate Mechanism in 1992, in what became known as Black Wednesday.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] When the European Coal and Steel Community was instituted in 1952, the United Kingdom decided not to become a member.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The UK was still absent when the Treaty of Rome was signed in 1957, creating the European Economic Community (the "Common Market").
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] However, in the late 1950s the Conservative government of Harold Macmillan dramatically changed its attitude, and appointed Edward Heath to submit an application and to lead negotiations for Britain to enter the Common Market.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The application was made at a meeting of the European Communities (EC) in January 1963, but the French president Charles de Gaulle rebuffed and vetoed Britain's request.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The 1970 general election saw all the major political parties commit to either membership or to negotiate with the European Communities.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The Conservative manifesto for the election on the issue was committed to negotiating membership but not at any price.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The Conservatives won a total of 330 seats (out of a total of 630) on 46.6% of the national vote share, gaining 77 seats, which gave them an unexpected overall majority of about 30 seats.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Edward Heath became Prime Minister, and personally led many of the negotiations which began following the election; he struck up a friendship with the new French president Georges Pompidou, who oversaw the lifting of the veto and thus paved the way for UK membership.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The debate itself took place between 21 and 28 October 1971, with the House of Commons debating directly whether or not the United Kingdom should become a member of the EC.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Conservative MPs were given a free vote, Labour MPs were given a three-line whip to vote against the motion, and Liberal MPs were whipped into voting in favour of the motion.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The House of Commons voted 356–244 in favour of the motion, a substantial majority of 112.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Throughout this period, the Labour Party was divided, both on the substantive issue of EC accession and on the question of whether accession ought to be approved by referendum.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] In 1971 pro-Market figures such as Roy Jenkins, the Deputy Leader of the Labour Party, said a Labour government would have agreed to the terms of accession secured by the Conservatives.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] However, the National Executive Committee and the Labour Party Conference disapproved of the terms.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] In April 1972, the anti-EC Conservative MP Neil Marten tabled an amendment to the European Communities Bill, which called for a consultative referendum on entry.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Labour had previously opposed a referendum, but the Shadow cabinet decided to support Marten's amendment.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Jenkins resigned as Deputy Leader in opposition to the decision, and many Labour MPs abstained in the division.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The United Kingdom joined the European Communities as a member state on 1 January 1973, along with Denmark and Ireland.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The EC would later become the European Union.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The initial euphoria and initial expectations of British membership after joining was very short lived as events in the Middle East would cause impacts which would be particularly felt within Britain.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The Yom Kippur War would lead to an Oil embargo by Arab counties which would lead to the "Three Day working week" being introduced and would eventually lead to Edward Heath to call a snap election which would ultimately end his time as Prime Minister.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] At the February 1974 United Kingdom general election, the Labour Party manifesto promised renegotiation of the UK's terms of membership, to be followed by a consultative referendum on continued membership under the new terms if they were acceptable.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Labour would become the largest party but were without an overall majority but managed to form a minority government.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Within one month of coming into office, the minority Labour Government started the negotiations promised in its February manifesto on the basis set out in that document.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] This could be interpreted as including the option of an election in 1975.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Labour managed to win a very small working majority in a second general election which was held in October that year, and had no need of another general election and the referendum was organised.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] This white paper was approved by the House of Commons.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] A Referendum Bill was introduced to the Commons on 26 March; at its second reading on 10 April, MPs voted 312–248 in favour.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Prior to the Bill's passing, there was no procedure or legislation within the United Kingdom for holding any such plebiscite.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The vote, the only nationwide plebiscite to be held in the UK during the 20th century, was of constitutional significance.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Referendums had been widely opposed in the past, on the grounds that they violated the principle of parliamentary sovereignty.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The first major referendum (i.e. one covering more than one local government area) to be held in any part of the UK had been the sovereignty referendum in Northern Ireland in 1973.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] How the votes were to be counted caused much division as the Bill went through Parliament.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] This proposal did not attract the wider support of the Labour Party or the other opposition parties; the Liberal Party favoured individual counts in each of the parliamentary constituencies, and tabled an amendment to this effect, but was defeated by 263 to 131 votes in the House of Commons.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] However, another amendment, tabled in the Commons by Labour MP Roderick MacFarquhar, sought to have separate counts for each administrative region (the post-1974 county council areas): this won cross-party support, and was carried by 272 to 155 votes.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The Act did not specify any national supermajority of 'Yes' votes for approval of the terms.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] It received royal assent on 8 May 1975, just under a month before the vote took place.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] A simple **YES** / **NO** answer was permitted (to be marked with a single 'X').
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The question that was used was one of the options in the Government white paper of February 1975, although during the passage of the Referendum Bill through Parliament, the Government agreed to add the words "Common Market" in brackets at the end of the question.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The referendum was called in April 1975 after the renegotiation was formally concluded.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Cabinet members would be allowed to publicly campaign against each other.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] In total, seven of the twenty-three members of the cabinet opposed EC membership.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Wilson's solution was that ministers speaking in the House of Commons should reflect government policy (i.e. support for EC membership), but would be allowed to speak freely elsewhere, thus avoiding a mass dismissal of Cabinet ministers.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] In spite of this, one minister, Eric Heffer, was obliged to resign after speaking against EC membership in the House of Commons.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The 'Yes' campaign was supported by Wilson and the majority of the cabinet, including the holders of the three other Great Offices of State: Denis Healey, the Chancellor of the Exchequer; James Callaghan, the Foreign Secretary; and Roy Jenkins, the Home Secretary.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The influential Conservative Edward du Cann said that "the Labour party is hopelessly and irrevocably split and muddled over this issue".
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The 'No' campaign included the left wing of the Labour Party, including the cabinet ministers Michael Foot, Tony Benn, Peter Shore, and Barbara Castle who during the campaign famously said "They lured us into the market with the mirage of the market miracle".
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Some Labour 'No' supporters, including Eric Varley and Douglas Jay, were on the right wing of the party, but most were from the left.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The 'No' campaign also included a large number of Labour backbenchers; upon the division on a pro-EC white paper about the renegotiation, 148 Labour MPs opposed their own government's measure, whereas only 138 supported it and 32 abstained.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] "Many Conservatives feel the European Community is not good for Britain ...
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Most of the Ulster Unionist Party were for 'No' in the referendum, most prominently the former Conservative minister Enoch Powell, who after Benn was the second-most prominent anti-Marketeer in the campaign.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Other parties supporting the 'No' campaign included the Democratic Unionist Party, the Scottish National Party, Plaid Cymru, and parties outside Parliament including the National Front and the Communist Party of Great Britain.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Conservative and Liberal Party conferences consistently supported EC membership for several years up to 1975.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] At a Labour Party conference on 26 April 1975, the Labour membership rejected continuing EC membership by almost a 2:1 margin.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Tony Benn said, "We have had a conference and the decision is clear ...
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Prior to the conference, the party had decided that if the conference voted by a margin of 2:1 or more in favour of a particular option, it would then support that position in the referendum campaign.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Otherwise, the 'party machine' would remain neutral.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Therefore, the Labour Party itself did not campaign on either side.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The government distributed pamphlets from the official Yes and No campaigns to every household in Britain, together with its own pamphlet which argued in support of EC membership.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] According to this pamphlet, "the most important (issues in the renegotiation) were FOOD and MONEY and JOBS".
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] During the campaign, almost the entire mainstream national British press supported the 'Yes' campaign.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The left-wing *Morning Star* was the only notable national daily to back the 'No' campaign.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Television broadcasts were used by both campaigns, like party political broadcasts during general elections.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] They were broadcast simultaneously on all three terrestrial channels: BBC 1, BBC 2 and ITV.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] They attracted audiences of up to 20 million viewers.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The 'Yes' campaign advertisements were thought to be much more effective, showing their speakers listening to and answering people's concerns, while the 'No' campaign's broadcasts featured speakers reading from an autocue.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The 'Yes' campaign enjoyed much more funding, thanks to the support of many British businesses and the Confederation of British Industry.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] According to the treasurer of the 'Yes' campaign, Alistair McAlpine, "The banks and big industrial companies put in very large sums of money".
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] At the time, business was "overwhelmingly pro-European", and Harold Wilson met several prominent industrialists to elicit support.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] It was common for pro-Europeans to convene across party and ideological lines with businessmen.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] John Mills, the national agent of the 'No' campaign, recalled: "We were operating on a shoe-string compared to the Rolls Royce operation on the other side".
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] However, it was also the case that many civil society groups supported the 'Yes' campaign, including the National Farmers Union and some trade unions.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Much of the 'Yes' campaign focused on the credentials of its opponents.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] According to Alistair McAlpine, "The whole thrust of our campaign was to depict the anti-Marketeers as unreliable people – dangerous people who would lead you down the wrong path ...
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] His claims were ridiculed by the 'Yes' campaign and ministers; the *Daily Mirror* labelled Benn the "Minister of Fear", and other newspapers were similarly derisive.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Ultimately, the 'No' campaign lacked a national leader with broad appeal.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Voting in the referendum took place across the United Kingdom on Thursday 5 June between 07:00 and 22:00 BST.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] All counting areas started their counts the following day on Friday 6 June at 09:00 BST, and the final result was announced just before 23:00 BST by the Chief Counting Officer (CCO) Sir Philip Allen at Earls Court Exhibition Centre in London, after all 68 counting areas had declared their totals.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] With a national turnout of 64% across the United Kingdom, the target to secure a majority for the winning side was 12,951,598 votes.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The result was a decisive endorsement of continued EC membership, which won by a huge majority of 8,908,508 votes (34.5%) over those who had voted to reject continued membership.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] In total, over two-thirds of voters supported continued EC membership.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] 67.2 per cent voted 'Yes' and 32.8 per cent voted 'No'.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] At council level, support for EC membership was positively correlated with support for the Conservative Party and with average income.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] In contrast, poorer areas that supported Labour gave less support to the question.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Approval was well above 60% in almost every council area in England and also in Wales, with the strongly Labour-supporting Mid Glamorgan being the exception.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Scotland and Northern Ireland gave less support to the question than the British average.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Once the voting areas had declared, their results were then relayed to Sir Philip Allen, the Chief Counting Officer, who later declared the final result.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] All the counting areas within the United Kingdom returned large majority 'Yes' votes except for two Scottish regions, the Shetland Islands and the Western Isles, which returned majority votes in favour of 'No'.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] NOTE: Unusually for a referendum **Yes** was the no change (status quo) option.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Roy Jenkins said: "It puts the uncertainty behind us.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The result strengthened Harold Wilson's tactical position, by securing a further post-election public expression of support for his policies.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] According to Cook and Francis (1979), 'The left of his party had been appeased by the holding of a referendum, the right by its result'.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Following the result, the Labour Party and British trade unions themselves joined European institutions, such as the Socialist Group in the European Parliament, to which they had been reluctant to commit before public approval of EC membership.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] In the House of Commons, the referendum result settled the issue of Europe for two years, until the debate about direct elections to the European Parliament began in 1977.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] On that occasion the relative difference of enthusiasm for membership was reversed, with England and Wales voting to leave, whilst Scotland, London and Northern Ireland voted to stay.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] At 11pm GMT on 31 January 2020, after 47 years of membership, the United Kingdom left the European Union.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Both the BBC and ITV provided coverage throughout the following day, and the BBC programme was presented by David Dimbleby and David Butler.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] There were several programmes throughout the day.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] While ITV's coverage was mixed in with live Horse Racing coverage from Epsom of the Epsom Oaks day card and was presented by Robert Kee and Peter Jay.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] This was the only major UK poll in which Alastair Burnet was not involved in the TV coverage as lead presenter as he was editing the Daily Express at the time of the referendum and was taking a break from broadcasting.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The BBC only kept two hours of coverage - that shown between 2pm and 4pm although even by then the outcome was very clear - and that coverage was repeated on BBC Parliament to mark the 30th anniversary of the referendum in June 2005.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] It was also reshown to mark the 40th anniversary in June 2015 on the BBC Parliament channel, and was also shown again to mark the 41st anniversary, ahead of the 2016 EU Referendum.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] 41 years after the 1975 referendum, David Dimbleby also hosted the BBC's coverage as the UK voted to leave the EU.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] The accession of the **United Kingdom** to the **European Communities (EC)** – the collective term for the European Coal and Steel Community (ECSC), the European Economic Community (EEC) and the European Atomic Energy Community (EAEC) – took effect on 1 January 1973.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] This followed ratification of the Accession treaty which was signed in Brussels on 22 January 1972 by the Conservative prime minister Edward Heath, who had pursued the UK's application to the EEC since the late 1950s.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] The ECSC and EEC would later be integrated into the European Union under the Maastricht and Lisbon treaties in the early 1990s and mid-2000s.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] The UK had been the first country to establish a Delegation to the ECSC in 1952, and the first country to sign an Association Agreement with the Community in 1954.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] The UK had first applied to join in 1961, but this was vetoed by French President Charles de Gaulle in 1963.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] A second application, in 1967, was again vetoed by France.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] After de Gaulle had relinquished the French presidency in 1969, the UK made a third and successful application for membership.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] Denmark and Ireland also joined as part of the same expansion.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] The UK's negotiation team in 1970–72 included Con O'Neill and David Hannay.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] The Treaty of Accession was signed in January 1972 by prime minister Edward Heath, leader of the Conservative Party.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] Parliament's European Communities Act 1972 was enacted on 17 October, and the UK's instrument of ratification was deposited the next day (18 October), letting the United Kingdom's membership of the EC come into effect on 1 January 1973.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] Shortly after the creation of the ECSC in 1952, the UK became the first country to establish a Delegation in Luxembourg, the seat of the High Authority (present-day European Commission) at the time.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] On 24 December 1953 the High Authority invited the British Government to enter into negotiations for the establishment of an association.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] On 29 April 1954 the British Government invited the High Authority to London to begin discussions on the proposed association and on 21 December 1954 the Agreement of Association was signed in London entering into force on 23 September 1955.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] This was the first example of an EU Association Agreement.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] The Agreement of Association established a Standing Council of Association which was intended to provide 'a means for the continuous exchange of information and for consultation in regard to matters of common interest concerning coal and steel' (Article 6).
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] The first meeting took place on 17 November 1955 in Luxembourg.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] At the second meeting on 22 March 1956 in London, the High Authority and the British Government agreed to open tariff negotiations.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] However, this effort was not successful.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] Subsequently, political opinion in Britain shifted towards greater engagement with the European Communities.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] There were potential economic benefits for Britain joining the EEC in respect of earnings.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] Following the establishment of the EEC in 1958, Britain had fallen behind EEC member states in terms of earnings.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] The Treaty of Accession 1972, which brought the United Kingdom into the European Communities, had already been met with opposition in the Parliament of the United Kingdom, notably from Labour's Peter Shore, who was Shadow Leader of the House of Commons at the time.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] "This is a treaty which carries the most formidable and far-reaching obligations.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] It is a treaty—the first in our history—which would deprive the British Parliament and people of democratic rights which they have exercised for many centuries.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] It was also noted that if the United Kingdom refused to join the European Communities, Denmark, Ireland and Norway would not accede either.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] Upon accession to the EC, numerous events were held as part of a two-week "Fanfare for Europe" programme, including over 300 events featuring music, art, entertainment and sport from national and European performers.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] The Queen attended an opening gala at the Royal Opera House.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] Despite an investment of £350,000 of public money, events were not well attended.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] A series of international football matches between the member states, including a home team captained by Bobby Charlton, left Wembley Stadium only half-full.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] Even so, only 12% of the electorate agreeing that membership had not brought the United Kingdom any benefit.
[src:accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities/accession-of-the-united-kingdom-to-the-european-communities] The Heath government subsequently lost its majority in the February 1974 election and renegotiation of membership being a prominent aspect of the victorious Labour Party's manifesto in the October 1974 United Kingdom general election.
